            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is the qSOFA (quick SOFA) score?</h2>
              <p>
                The qSOFA (quick Sequential Organ Failure Assessment) score is a
                simple bedside tool proposed by the Sepsis-3 task force to help
                identify adult patients with suspected infection who are at
                higher risk of sepsis-related organ dysfunction and poor
                outcomes, especially outside the ICU (e.g., emergency
                department, hospital wards, pre-hospital settings).
              </p>
              <p>
                qSOFA uses only three easily measured clinical criteria and does
                not require laboratory tests. It is <strong>not</strong> a
                diagnostic test for sepsis, but a prompt to look more closely at
                the patient and consider escalation of care.
              </p>

              <h2>qSOFA criteria and scoring</h2>
              <p>
                The qSOFA score ranges from 0 to 3. Each criterion is worth 1
                point if present:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-2">qSOFA components</p>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-5">
                  <li>
                    <strong>Respiratory rate ≥ 22 breaths/min</strong> &rarr; 1
                    point
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Altered mental status</strong> (GCS &lt; 15 or acute
                    change) &rarr; 1 point
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Systolic blood pressure ≤ 100 mmHg</strong> &rarr; 1
                    point
                  </li>
                
